# RollCraft -- Vision Document

**The Pokemon of Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu**

---

## The Pitch

There are over 15 million people training Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu worldwide, and there is not a single video game that respects the depth of the art. Fighting games treat grappling as a mini-game. MMA games reduce ground work to a button-mashing QTE. Nobody has built a game where a black belt plays it and thinks, "this is actually how it works." RollCraft is that game.

RollCraft takes the proven RPG mechanics that made Pokemon the highest-grossing media franchise in history and maps them onto the richest combat system on Earth. Eight grappler styles function as Pokemon types, with a full effectiveness chart. 142 real BJJ techniques -- from basic takedowns to flying triangles -- serve as the move pool. Positions on the mat create a dynamic battlefield where mount is your Surf and back control is your Hyper Beam. The result is a game that is immediately intuitive to anyone who has played a turn-based RPG, while being endlessly deep for anyone who has ever stepped on a mat.

The market opportunity is massive and completely untapped. BJJ practitioners are obsessed with the art -- they watch competition footage, study instructionals, and debate technique online for hours. Give them a game that captures that depth in a mobile-friendly, pick-up-and-play package with Pokemon nostalgia woven into every system, and you have something that spreads through every gym on the planet. RollCraft is not a niche product -- it sits at the intersection of the $200B+ mobile gaming market and the fastest-growing combat sport in the world.

---

## What Exists Today

RollCraft is a working alpha built in React 19, TypeScript, and Canvas 2D. The core is functional and playable:

- **142 BJJ techniques** across takedowns, sweeps, passes, submissions, escapes, and transitions -- covering Judo, Wrestling, Sambo, modern leg locks, and flashy submissions
- **8 grappler styles** with a full 8x8 type effectiveness chart (2.0x/1.5x/1.0x/0.5x multipliers)
- **12 ground positions** with top/bottom/neutral roles and position-specific move availability
- **Pokemon Gen 1 damage formula** with STAB bonus, style effectiveness, critical hits, and random variance
- **Stamina system** replacing PP, with gassed penalties and position-based recovery
- **Submission mini-game** with 3-phase attacker vs. defender stat rolls
- **Belt progression** from white to black with cinematic promotions
- **Pixel art overworld** gym with tile-based movement, NPC dialogue, and mobile controls
- **Full character creation** with name, gym, coach, gi color, and starter path selection

The foundation is solid. Everything below is the roadmap to make it extraordinary.

---

## Career Mode -- The BJJ Journey

The heart of RollCraft is the career. You are a white belt. You just walked into a gym for the first time. Your coach barely knows your name. From here, everything is earned.

### The Path

Your career follows the real BJJ journey:

1. **White Belt** -- You train at your home gym. You learn the basics. You get smashed by upper belts. Your coach teaches you fundamentals and you drill until they become instinct.

2. **Blue Belt** -- The world opens up. You can visit other gyms, drop in on classes, learn from different instructors. You enter your first local tournament. You might lose in the first round, and that is fine.

3. **Purple Belt** -- You start to develop your own game. Specialization branches unlock -- choose a path that defines your style for the rest of your career. Private lessons from famous instructors become available. Regional championships are on the table.

4. **Brown Belt** -- You are dangerous. National championships. Sponsorship offers start coming in. Training camps before big events. Your coach trusts you to teach lower belts.

5. **Black Belt** -- The summit. World Championships. ADCC-style invitational super fights. You have 12 move slots, a fully realized style, and a reputation that precedes you onto the mat.

### Cinematic Moments

Every belt promotion is a cinematic event. Your coach -- the one you named at the start of the game -- ties the belt around your waist. The dialogue is personalized. You have been training with this person for your entire career, and the promotion reflects that relationship.

Tournament wins are celebrated with podium ceremonies. Gold medals are displayed in your gym. Your record follows you.

---

## Economy System

### Training Costs

- **Mat fees** -- Pay your home gym for daily/weekly training. This is your baseline cost.
- **Drop-in fees** -- Visit another gym, pay the drop-in rate, train for the day. More expensive but gives access to that gym's unique moves and instructors.
- **Private lessons** -- One-on-one with a specific instructor. Expensive, but guaranteed to teach you a TM move (a specific technique from that instructor's system).
- **Seminars** -- Special timed events where a legendary grappler visits a gym. Anyone who attends can learn a rare move. Seminar moves are exclusive to these events.

### Competition Economy

- **Entry fees** -- Pay to register for tournaments. Higher-level events cost more.
- **Prize money** -- Win matches, win money. Gold at Worlds pays significantly more than gold at locals.
- **Medals and trophies** -- Displayed in your gym. Visual proof of your accomplishments.

### Sponsorships

At higher belts, brands start approaching you. Gi companies, supplement brands, instructional platforms. Sponsorships provide passive income that offsets training costs. The better your competition record, the bigger the deals.

---

## Tournament System

Tournaments are the competitive spine of the game. They escalate in stakes, difficulty, and prestige.

### Local Tournaments

Small brackets (4-8 competitors). Low entry fees, modest prizes. Good XP. Available from blue belt onward. These are where you learn to compete.

### Regional Championships

Larger brackets (16-32). Belt-specific divisions. Real cash prizes. You start seeing grapplers from other gyms with styles you have never encountered. You need a game plan.

### National Championships

Elite level. Every style is represented. The brackets are deep. Winning here puts you on the map. Sponsorship opportunities multiply.

### World Championships (Mundials)

The ultimate goal. Black belt worlds. The best grapplers from every gym, every style, every country. Gold medal at Worlds is legendary status. This is the final boss.

### ADCC-Style Invitationals

No-gi super fights. Invitational format -- you do not qualify, you get invited based on reputation and results. Unique rule sets (submission-only periods, overtime, different point structures). The most prestigious events in the game.

### Tournament Mechanics

- **Brackets** -- Single elimination with seeding based on rank/record
- **Multiple rounds** -- Win your way through the bracket
- **Podium ceremonies** -- Gold, silver, bronze with visual celebration
- **Record tracking** -- Win/loss record, submission rate, tournament history

---

## Gym System

### Home Gym

Your base of operations. This is where your coach is, where your training partners are, where you get promoted. You can upgrade your home gym over time -- better equipment, more training partners, visiting instructors.

### The World Map

Travel to different gyms across a world map. Each gym has a distinct identity:

- **Wrestling-heavy gyms** -- Takedown-focused training partners, wrestling instructors, strong top game culture
- **Leg lock academies** -- Modern no-gi focused, heel hook drills, leg entanglement specialists
- **Old-school BJJ academies** -- Traditional gi work, self-defense curriculum, respect-heavy culture
- **Competition team headquarters** -- Elite training partners, world-class coaches, everything geared toward tournament performance
- **Niche specialty gyms** -- Berimbolo labs, pressure passing workshops, submission-only clubs

Each gym has unique instructors who teach moves you cannot learn anywhere else.

### Training Camps

Before a major tournament, you can set up a training camp at a specific gym. Training camps give bonus EV gains, access to sparring partners who simulate your bracket opponents, and focused coaching from the gym's head instructor. The gym you choose for your camp influences how prepared you are.

---

## Move Learning System

### Level-Up Moves

As you progress through belts and gain XP, new moves become automatically available. These are the fundamentals -- every grappler should know them regardless of style. Bridge escape at white belt. Knee cut pass at blue belt. Back take from turtle at purple belt.

### TM Moves (Instructor Techniques)

Specific famous instructors teach signature techniques:

- **"Craig Jones"** teaches Octopus Guard, Z-Lock, Body Triangle Back Control
- **"Gordon Ryan"** teaches Body Lock System, Systematic Passing, Mounted Crucifix
- **"Marcelo Garcia"** teaches X-Guard Sweep, Guillotine from Every Position, Butterfly Hook Mastery
- **"Mikey Musumeci"** teaches Single Leg X, Inside Sankaku, Berimbolo Chains
- **"Lachlan Giles"** teaches K-Guard, Knee Slide Counter, Outside Heel Hook Mastery

TM moves cost money (private lessons) and are permanently learned. Each instructor only teaches their signature moves.

### Seminar Moves

Timed events. A legendary grappler visits a gym for a weekend. If you are there, you can learn a rare technique. Seminar moves include:

- Techniques from retired legends
- Competition-specific setups
- Experimental positions
- Cross-discipline moves (Sambo, Catch Wrestling, Judo Newaza)

Miss the seminar, miss the move. They rotate and repeat, but you have to show up.

### Move Evolution

Use any move 100 times in competition or training, and it **evolves** into a "Master" version:

- Enhanced power (+15%)
- Improved accuracy (+5%)
- Reduced stamina cost (-2)
- New chain potential (opens links to advanced follow-ups)

This rewards dedication to your game. A Master-level Armbar from Guard is different from a white belt's Armbar from Guard -- not because you bought something, but because you drilled it hundreds of times.

### Specialization Branches

At purple belt, you choose a specialization path. These unlock exclusive technique trees unavailable to other paths:

- **The Shark** (Sub Hunter path) -- Submission chains, catch-and-release setups, finish-from-anywhere techniques
- **The Wall** (Controller path) -- Positional lockdowns, stalling recovery techniques, exhaustion warfare
- **The Scrambler** (Berimbolo path) -- Inversion combos, back-take chains, transition-heavy offense
- **The Anvil** (Pressure Passer path) -- Crushing passes, weight distribution mastery, top pressure submissions
- **The Spider** (Guard Player path) -- Guard retention mastery, sweep-to-submission links, bottom game domination
- **The Predator** (Leg Locker path) -- Deep leg entanglement trees, saddle positions, 50/50 warfare
- **The Thrower** (Judoka path) -- Combination throws, grip fighting mastery, throw-to-pin sequences
- **The Machine** (Wrestler path) -- Chain wrestling, ride control, mat return techniques

---

## Multiplayer

### Local PvP

Challenge a friend via a shareable link. Same battle engine, but now the opponent is a human who reads your chains, manages their stamina, and adapts. The meta shifts entirely when your opponent can think.

### Online Ranked

Matchmaking by belt rank and style. Climb a ladder. Seasonal resets with rewards. The ranked system mirrors real competition -- you face opponents at your level, and progression is earned.

### Gym vs. Gym

Team competitions. Assemble a roster from your gym's grapplers (yours + your training partners). Each gym fields a team of 5. Order matters -- do you lead with your strongest grappler or save them for the anchor position?

### Spectator Mode

Watch high-level ranked matches live. See how top players use chain systems, manage stamina, and navigate the position game. Learn by watching, just like at a real open mat.

---

## Monetization

### Free to Play

The entire core game is free. Career mode, all positions, all base moves, all belt promotions, tournaments, training. Nothing that affects gameplay is behind a paywall.

### Premium (Cosmetic Only)

- **Custom gis** -- Unique colors, patterns, patches, rash guards
- **Gym customization** -- Decorate your home gym, custom mats, wall art, trophies
- **Entrance animations** -- Walk-out sequences for tournament matches
- **Belt accessories** -- Custom belt tips, embroidered stripes

### What You Cannot Buy

- Stat boosts
- Move unlocks
- XP multipliers
- Tournament advantages
- Anything that makes your grappler better than another player's

The principle is absolute: **your grappler's strength comes from training, not spending.** This mirrors the real ethos of BJJ -- there are no shortcuts. Time on the mat is the only currency that matters.

---

## Why RollCraft Wins

### For the BJJ Community

This is the game practitioners have been waiting for without knowing it. Every technique is real. Every position transition makes sense. The type matchup chart reflects actual stylistic advantages on the mat. When a Leg Locker is super effective against a Wrestler, every grappler who has ever seen a wrestler get heel-hooked nods and smiles. This is not a game that trivializes the art -- it celebrates it.

### For Gamers

Pokemon nostalgia is one of the most powerful forces in gaming. The turn-based RPG format is instantly understood by hundreds of millions of people. RollCraft is not asking anyone to learn something new -- it is giving them a familiar format with a fresh, deep, real-world combat system underneath. The grappler styles are types. The moves are moves. The belt progression is leveling up. It just clicks.

### For Mobile

Built mobile-first from day one. Touch controls, portrait and landscape support, sessions that work in 5-minute bursts or hour-long sessions. Train on the bus. Roll during lunch. Compete before bed. The game lives where people already spend their time.

### The Flywheel

BJJ gyms are communities. When one person at a gym starts playing RollCraft, they show their training partners. "Look, they have the berimbolo in here." "My grappler is a Leg Locker and I just heel-hooked a Wrestler -- super effective." The game spreads organically through the same social networks that BJJ already uses. Every gym is a distribution channel.

---

## Technical Foundation

| Component | Technology |
|-----------|-----------|
| Frontend | React 19 + TypeScript 6 |
| Build | Vite 8 |
| Rendering | Canvas 2D |
| State | localStorage (evolving to cloud sync) |
| Platform | Mobile web (PWA-ready) |
| Deployment | Static hosting (Netlify/Vercel) |

The architecture is intentionally lightweight. No backend required for single-player. Cloud sync and multiplayer will require a server layer (WebSocket for real-time PvP, REST for persistence), but the core game runs entirely client-side.

---

## Roadmap

### Phase 1: Alpha (Current)
Core battle engine, 142 moves, character creation, overworld gym, belt progression, single-player AI battles.

### Phase 2: Career Mode
Multiple opponents at varying belt levels, tournament system (local through nationals), economy (mat fees, drop-ins, prizes), move learning from instructors.

### Phase 3: Depth
Move evolution system, specialization branches at purple belt, training camps, world map with multiple gyms, seminar events.

### Phase 4: Multiplayer
Local PvP, online ranked matchmaking, gym vs. gym team battles, spectator mode.

### Phase 5: Polish and Launch
Sound design, music, advanced animations, PWA packaging, app store distribution, community features.

---

## Contact

RollCraft is built by grapplers, for grapplers. Every mechanic is informed by thousands of hours on the mat. This is the game the BJJ world deserves.
